The paper proposes a 3-D deep neural network for diagnosing lung cancer from computed tomography scans. This involves detecting all suspicious lesions (pulmonary nodules) and evaluating the whole-lung/pulmonary malignancy. The paper focuses on the second step, which is the evaluation of malignancy, and proposes a novel approach using a modified U-net and a leaky noisy-OR gate. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category, as it involves analyzing medical images. Additionally, the use of deep neural networks and machine learning techniques suggests that it could also belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. The paper also mentions the use of a region proposal network, which is commonly used in natural language processing (cs.CL) and object detection (cs.CV). Finally, the paper mentions the issue of overfitting and proposes a solution using alternate training, which suggests that it could also belong to the neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE) sub-category.
